

Core Docker Commands
docker run: Creates and starts a new container from an image. Use -d for background mode and -p to map ports (e.g., docker run -p 80:80 nginx).
docker ps: Lists running containers. Adding the -a flag lists all containers, including stopped ones.
docker stop <id>: Gracefully stops a running container.
docker start <id>: Restarts a previously stopped container.
docker exec -it <id> bash: Opens an interactive shell session inside a running container.
docker rm <id>: Removes a stopped container. Use -f to force-remove a running one.  

Docker to run ubuntu OS image under a container
----------
   docker run -it ubuntu   (Spin up a new container of Ubuntu OS image)
   docker container ls     (Gives the list of running docker container)
   docker container ls -a  (Gives the list of stopped container too)
   docker start|stop ubuntu
   docker exec ubuntu ls    (Gives the container file system)
   docker exec -it ubuntu (t - terminal , i - interrative)

Note:
   1. container runs the images. A container might have multiple images. Container don't share any information each other
   2. Docker images available https://hub.docker.com/_/node 
